{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611445"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:10:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:10:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16218"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16218"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8909"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73396"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8909"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16218"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58862"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"262"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21201"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21203"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73396"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA histological section of breast tissue from a 35-year-old woman shows dilated ducts containing eosinophilic material, surrounded by dense fibrous stroma. Multiple microcysts are present with areas of adenosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the histological features shown?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fibrocystic change","Fibroadenoma","Sclerosing adenosis","Intraductal papilloma","Ductal ectasia"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrocystic change\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by three main histological features:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECyst formation (fluid-filled spaces lined by epithelium)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStromal fibrosis (increased dense connective tissue)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuctal proliferation (epithelial hyperplasia)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibroadenoma\u003C/strong\u003E shows a well-circumscribed biphasic tumour with both epithelial and stromal components in a pericanalicular or intracanalicular growth pattern\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESclerosing adenosis\u003C/strong\u003E shows compressed and distorted glands within a dense fibrous stroma, but lacks the cystic changes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntraductal papilloma\u003C/strong\u003E shows arborising fibrovascular cores covered by epithelium projecting into a dilated duct\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuctal ectasia\u003C/strong\u003E shows dilated ducts containing inspissated secretions but lacks the stromal changes and proliferation seen in fibrocystic change\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFibrocystic change is a common finding in women of reproductive age and represents a physiological response to hormonal stimulation rather than a pathological process.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fibrocystic change is characterised histologically by cyst formation, stromal fibrosis, and ductal proliferation in breast tissue.","Fibrocystic change affects up to 50% of women of reproductive age and is considered a normal physiological variation rather than a disease."],"references":["\u0022Fibrocystic change - high mag\u0022 by Nephron is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Fibrocystic_change_-_high_mag.jpg","Dang BQ, Miles B, Young P, He J, Nguyen QD. An Interesting Imaging Presentation of a Common Benign Entity: Fibrocystic Changes in a Postmenopausal Patient. Cureus. 2023 Mar 17;15(3):e36292. doi: 10.7759/cureus.36292. PMID: 37073209; PMCID: PMC10106097.","JiueLan K, Sekine C, Kurozumi S, Matsuoka R, Komuta M, Shiomi T, Horiguchi J. Fibrocystic breast disease with pleomorphic calcifications and segmental distribution: A case report. Radiol Case Rep. 2023 Aug 25;18(11):3828-3830. doi: 10.1016/j.radcr.2023.08.010. PMID: 37670913; PMCID: PMC10475390.","Malherbe K, Khan M, Fatima S. Fibrocystic Breast Disease. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31869073.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58862"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16218"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21216"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21216"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2Gz8I2IKvu6XQuimaq4sm3hXA0t6x7.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2Gz8I2IKvu6XQuimaq4sm3hXA0t6x7.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1000}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58862","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58862"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T15:10:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T09:48:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type"